{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d2b31c85-4411-4254-b8e7-015d79cdd6ca","content":"Here's the quickest path:\n\n### 1. Get a shell into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present)\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find your process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect a CPU trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can copy out and analyze:\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-nettrace> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\nOpen it in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app) (`dotnet-trace convert --format speedscope`).\n\n### Alternative: `dotnet-counters` for a quick look first\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\nThis gives live CPU %, GC, thread-pool stats — useful to confirm the problem before collecting a full trace.\n\n> **Tip:** If the container image doesn't have the .NET SDK/CLI, you can sidecar or copy the standalone `dotnet-trace` tool in. Also ensure the `DOTNET_EnableDiagnostics` env var isn't set to `0`, or diagnostics will be disabled.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"38a40456-a2f1-4407-8fc8-1d42f7e23fd9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a troubleshooting/advisory question - I don't need to search the codebase or use tools for this. I can provide the answer directly from my knowledge.\n\nLet me give a concise but practical answer covering the key steps.","outputTokens":473,"requestId":"1BC6:14F244:CB254F:E797E3:6A0280F8"},"id":"a32476eb-ac07-4429-b94a-97184ee4a833","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:23:16.337Z","parentId":"89601950-139a-4066-b520-45c30db3b8b2"}
